    q: "My Samsung WF front-load washer is making a loud grinding noise during spin, is it the drum bearing?",
    a: "Almost certainly, yes, and you're not alone. The Samsung WF-series front-load drum bearing pattern is one of the most-documented washer reliability issues of the past decade. Failures cluster at <b>16-24 months</b>, often just outside Samsung's standard 1-year warranty. The reported root cause from repair technicians: bearings over-pressed into the rear outer drum during manufacturing, cracking the drum at the rear seal opening, which makes the bearing seal useless and accelerates wear. Symptoms progress from a quiet hum to a loud roar to a metal-on-metal grind that's impossible to ignore. The hard part: <b>Samsung doesn't sell the bearing as a separate part</b>, the repair requires a full tub assembly, which alone runs $500+ at parts and $880-$1,280 with labor on a 3-4 year machine. We diagnose with manual rotation test, lateral play check, and stethoscope on the rear seal area. If it's bearing failure on a 4-plus-year WF, we quote both repair and replacement honestly, the economics often favor replacement, but customers with a matching DV dryer in good condition often choose the repair to keep the stack working."
