<!-- 05 FRONT-LOAD VS TOP-LOAD -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">05, Front-load vs top-load Samsung washers</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Two architectures, two reliability profiles.</h2>

    <p>The choice between Samsung WF front-load and WA top-load isn't just about wash performance, it's about which service tree your future repairs fall into. We see the difference clearly across thousands of Samsung washer service calls per year.</p>

    <h3 class="subhead">Samsung WF front-load, what to expect</h3>
    <p>WF series uses lower water and detergent per load, runs more efficient cycles, and is generally the architecture in newer construction and renovation kitchens. The reliability story is mixed: extremely reliable for the first 18-24 months, then the bearing pattern hits a meaningful percentage of units. Door boot bellows is the year 5-8 wear item on most front-loaders regardless of brand, and Samsung is no exception. Mold and odor issues in the door boot and dispenser are a maintenance question, leave the door open between loads, run a monthly tub clean cycle, and avoid liquid fabric softener (which accelerates bellows breakdown).</p>

    <h3 class="subhead">Samsung WA top-load, what to expect</h3>
    <p>WA series uses more water per load but completes cycles faster, and the mechanical architecture is simpler, fewer electronic controls, fewer wear surfaces under high-stress spin. <strong>Excluding the 2011-2016 recall era</strong>, WA top-loaders are generally more reliable mechanically than WF front-loaders. The trade-offs: higher water and detergent usage, less gentle on delicate fabrics, and the recall verification step on any unit from that era. We've serviced WA50R units 8-10 years old that are still running strong on original drain pumps and water valves, that level of longevity is uncommon on WF front-load.</p>

    <h3 class="subhead">FlexWash WV, the dual-drum case</h3>
    <p>FlexWash adds a smaller upper-compartment drum to a standard WF front-load chassis. The intent is to wash delicates separately without committing the full main drum. From a service standpoint, FlexWash inherits all WF service items plus upper-compartment-specific failures: separate dispenser leak (when the upper spins, the dispenser sometimes leaks back into the main drum), separate upper drum drain pump, separate upper motor. We service these honestly, FlexWash adds repair complexity, and customers who don't actually use the upper compartment regularly often regret the extra parts surface.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 06 REPAIR VS REPLACE -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">06, Repair or replace?</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">When Samsung washer repair makes sense, and when replacement is the honest call.</h2>

    <p class="lead">We give you concrete numbers after diagnostic. Repair cost, replacement cost (comparable model new), and projected remaining service life. Then you decide.</p>

    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>WF front-load drum bearing failure, 4+ years old:</strong> Repair $880-$1,280 vs replacement $1,000-$1,200 for comparable WF45. Math tilts toward replacement unless you have a matching DV dryer in good condition you want to keep paired. About <strong>60% of customers in this scenario choose replacement</strong> in our experience.</li>
      <li><strong>WF front-load drum bearing failure, under 3 years old:</strong> Repair almost always wins, the rest of the machine still has 5+ years of expected service life, and replacement throws away a near-new unit. We've done bearing repairs on 18-month WF units where the customer was effectively saving $700+ vs replacement.</li>
      <li><strong>WA top-load mechanical failure (drain pump, water valve, lid lock):</strong> Almost always worth repairing on units up to 10 years old. These are $200-$400 fixes on machines with strong motors and simple transmissions. Replacement makes sense only on the 2011-2016 recall units when Samsung's recall path covers more than the repair would cost.</li>
      <li><strong>Control board failure on any Samsung washer 8+ years old:</strong> Case-by-case. Boards run $345-$525, meaningful percentage of replacement value on older units. We assess the rest of the machine (drain pump condition, door boot wear, bearing health on WF) before quoting; if multiple components are nearing end-of-life, replacement often makes more sense than chasing one repair.</li>
      <li><strong>FlexWash with multiple component failures:</strong> Replacement usually wins. FlexWash's dual-drum architecture means more parts, more service complexity, and units that have already had two or three repairs are typically in the "replace" zone.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>We never push replacement when repair makes sense, and we never push repair when the math doesn't work. The diagnostic visit is $89 either way.</p>
  </div>
</section>

